      {"id": "IuCyW0R_HGM8H0HK", "content": {"type": "Text", "format": "html", "text": ["<strong>Situation A. Buying Tickets</strong>", "<p>Noralie is buying tickets for a concert online. The cost of the tickets is represented in a table, graph, and equation.</p>"]}},
      [
        {
          "id": "QPIw_hR9ye-iDU1G",
          "title": "Cost of Tickets from the Box Office",
          "content": {"type": "Table", "name": "Cost of Tickets from the Box Office", "columns": [{"name": "Number of Tickets", "width": 99.49609375, "values": ["0", "1", "2", "1x4 = 4"]}, {"name": "Total Cost of Tickets", "width": 122.85546875, "values": ["0", "30", "60", "30 x 4 = 120"]}]}
        },
        {"id": "GRJjpe07QzPACiT_", "title": "Cost Graph", "content": {"type": "Image", "url": "curriculum/comparing-and-scaling/images/C&S_2-3_BoxOfficeTicketsGraph_350w.jpg"}}
      ],
      {"content": {"type": "Text", "format": "html", "text": ["<p><em>C</em> is the cost of the tickets</p>", "<p><em>N</em> is the number of tickets</p>", "<p><em>C = 30N</em></p>", "<p><em>120 = 30N</em></p>"]}},
      {"id": "WHa2OXqPVTld1uOG", "content": {"type": "Text", "format": "html", "text": ["<ul><li>How is the constant of proportionality (or unit rate) represented in each?</li></ul>"]}},
      {
        "display": "teacher",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p>The constant of proportionality is represented:</p>",
            "<p>In the table when one quantity is 1.</p>",
            "<p>In the graph by the amount of increase in the total cost (y value) each time the number of tickets (x value) increases by 1.</p>",
            "<p>In the equation by the number being multiplied by N (number of tickets).</p>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {"id": "L5kUqYJEbXrNFnVY", "content": {"type": "Text", "format": "html", "text": ["<ul><li>How does this information help us answer questions about proportional situations?</li></ul>"]}},
      {"display": "teacher", "content": {"type": "Text", "format": "html", "text": ["<p>If we know one of the quantities is 1, we can scale to any amount to answer a question.</p>"]}},
      {"id": "LK0TQpCSeT5OE8OC", "content": {"type": "Text", "format": "html", "text": ["<ul><li>How many tickets could you buy for $120. How did you determine your answer?</li></ul>"]}},
      {
        "display": "teacher",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p>(4,120)  or 4 tickets.</p>",
            "<p>  To find the number of tickets, see blue notations on the representations above.</p>",
            "<p>With the table, scale the $30 up to $120.</p>",
            "<p>With the graph, find the point (x, 120).</p>",
            "<p>With the equation we can substitute 120 for C and then solve for the number of tickets.</p>",
            "<p>120 = 30N.</p>",
            "<p>N = 4.</p>",
            "<p>Note: Students have not worked on formal strategies for solving equations at this point. They will use strategies on their knowledge of operations and/or fact families to solve the problem. For example, they may say that the equation is asking them to find what number (N) times 30 will result in the product of 120. So, they need to use division: 120 ÷ 30 = N, so N =4. This will be developed further in Moving Straight Ahead.</p>"
          ]
        }
      },
